# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sidecar-proxy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] A **design pattern** is the re-usable form of a solution to a design problem.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] The idea was introduced by the architect Christopher Alexander and has been adapted for various other disciplines, particularly software engineering.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] An organized collection of design patterns that relate to a particular field is called a pattern language.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] This language gives a common terminology for discussing the situations designers are faced with.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Documenting a pattern requires explaining why a particular situation causes problems, and how the components of the pattern relate to each other to give the solution.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Christopher Alexander describes common design problems as arising from "conflicting forces"—such as the conflict between wanting a room to be sunny and wanting it not to overheat on summer afternoons.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] A pattern would not tell the designer how many windows to put in the room; instead, it would propose a set of values to guide the designer toward a decision that is best for their particular application.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Alexander, for example, suggests that enough windows should be included to direct light all around the room.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] He considers this a good solution because he believes it increases the enjoyment of the room by its occupants.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Other authors might come to different conclusions, if they place higher value on heating costs, or material costs.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] These values, used by the pattern's author to determine which solution is "best", must also be documented within the pattern.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Pattern documentation should also explain when it is applicable.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Since two houses may be very different from one another, a design pattern for houses must be broad enough to apply to both of them, but not so vague that it doesn't help the designer make decisions.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] The range of situations in which a pattern can be used is called its context.
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Some examples might be "all houses", "all two-story houses", or "all places where people spend time".
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] For instance, in Christopher Alexander's work, bus stops and waiting rooms in a surgery center are both within the context for the pattern "A PLACE TO WAIT".
[src:sidecar-proxy/design-pattern] Business models also have design patterns.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:sidecar-proxy/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In computer networking, a **proxy server** is a intermediary server application between a client requesting a resource and the server then providing that resource.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server that can fulfil a request for a resource, such as a file or web page, the client directs the request to the proxy server, which evaluates the request and performs the required network transactions.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This serves as a method to control the complexity of the request or provide additional benefits such as load balancing, privacy or security.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies were devised to add structure and encapsulation to distributed systems.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy server may reside on the user's **local computer**, or at any point between the user's computer and the destination servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy server that passes unmodified requests and responses is usually called a gateway or sometimes a *tunneling proxy*.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A forward proxy is an Internet-facing proxy used to retrieve data from a wide range of sources (in most cases, anywhere on the Internet).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy is usually an internal-facing proxy used as a front-end to control and protect access to a server on a private network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy commonly also performs tasks such as load-balancing, authentication, decryption, and caching.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] An open proxy is a forwarding proxy server that is accessible by any Internet user.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In 2008, network security expert Gordon Lyon estimated that "hundreds of thousands" of open proxies are operated on the Internet.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy (or surrogate) is a proxy server that appears to clients to be an ordinary server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Reverse proxies send requests to one or more ordinary servers that handle the request.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The response from the original server is returned as if it came directly from the proxy server, leaving the client with no knowledge of the original server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Reverse proxies are installed in the vicinity of one or more web servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] All traffic coming from the Internet and with a destination of one of the neighborhood's web servers goes through the proxy server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The use of "reverse" originates in its counterpart, the "forward" proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The reverse proxy sits closer to the web server and serves only a restricted set of websites.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A forward proxy is a server that routes traffic between clients and another system, which is, in most cases, external to the network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This means it can regulate traffic according to preset policies, convert and mask client IP addresses, enforce security protocols, and block unknown traffic.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A forward proxy enhances security and policy enforcement within an internal network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy, instead of protecting the client, is used to protect the servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy accepts a request from a client, forwards that request to another one of many other servers, and then returns the results from the server that specifically processed the request to the client.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Effectively, a reverse proxy acts as a gateway between clients, users, and application servers and handles all the traffic routing whilst also protecting the identity of the server that physically processes the request.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A content-filtering web proxy server provides administrative control over the content that may be relayed in one or both directions through the proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] It is commonly used in both commercial and non-commercial organizations (especially schools) to ensure that Internet usage conforms to acceptable use policy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Content filtering proxy servers will often support user authentication to control web access.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] It also usually produces logs, either to give detailed information about the URLs accessed by specific users or to monitor bandwidth usage statistics.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] It may also communicate to daemon-based or ICAP-based antivirus software to provide security against viruses and other malware by scanning incoming content in real-time before it enters the network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Many workplaces, schools, and colleges restrict websites and online services that are accessible and available in their buildings.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Governments also censor undesirable content.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This is done either with a specialized proxy, called a content filter (both commercial and free products are available), or by using a cache-extension protocol such as ICAP, which allows plug-in extensions to an open caching architecture.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Websites commonly used by students to circumvent filters and access blocked content often include a proxy, from which the user can then access the websites that the filter is trying to block.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Requests may be filtered by several methods, such as a URL or DNS blacklists, URL regex filtering, MIME filtering, or content keyword filtering.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Blacklists are often provided and maintained by web-filtering companies, often grouped into categories (pornography, gambling, shopping, social networks, etc.).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The proxy then fetches the content, assuming the requested URL is acceptable.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] At this point, a dynamic filter may be applied on the return path.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] For example, JPEG files could be blocked based on fleshtone matches, or language filters could dynamically detect unwanted language.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] If the content is rejected, then an HTTP fetch error may be returned to the requester.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Most web filtering companies use an internet-wide crawling robot that assesses the likelihood that content is a certain type.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Manual labor is used to correct the resultant database based on complaints or known flaws in the content-matching algorithms.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Some proxies scan outbound content, e.g., for data loss prevention, or scan content for malicious software.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Web filtering proxies are not able to peer inside secure sockets HTTP transactions, assuming the chain-of-trust of SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security) has not been tampered with.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The SSL/TLS chain-of-trust relies on trusted root certificate authorities.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In a workplace setting where the client is managed by the organization, devices may be configured to trust a root certificate whose private key is known to the proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In such situations, proxy analysis of the contents of an SSL/TLS transaction becomes possible.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The proxy is effectively operating a man-in-the-middle attack, allowed by the client's trust of a root certificate that the proxy owns.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] If the destination server filters content based on the origin of the request, the use of a proxy can circumvent this filter.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] For example, a server using IP-based geolocation to restrict its service to a certain country can be accessed using a proxy located in that country to access the service.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Web proxies are the most common means of bypassing government censorship, although no more than 3% of Internet users use any circumvention tools.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Some proxy service providers allow businesses access to their proxy network for rerouting traffic for business intelligence purposes.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In some cases, users can circumvent proxies that filter using blacklists by using services designed to proxy information from a non-blacklisted location.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies can be installed to eavesdrop upon the data-flow between client machines and the web.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] All content sent or accessed, including passwords submitted and cookies used, can be captured and analyzed by the proxy operator.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] For this reason, passwords to online services (such as webmail and banking) should always be exchanged over a cryptographically secured connection, such as SSL.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] By chaining the proxies that do not reveal data about the original requester, it is possible to obfuscate activities from the eyes of the user's destination.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] However, more traces will be left on the intermediate hops, which could be used or offered up to trace the user's activities.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] If the policies and administrators of these other proxies are unknown, the user may fall victim to a false sense of security just because those details are out of sight and mind.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In what is more of an inconvenience than a risk, proxy users may find themselves being blocked from certain websites, as numerous forums and websites block IP addresses from proxies known to have spammed or trolled the site.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Proxy bouncing can be used to maintain privacy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A **caching proxy** server accelerates service requests by retrieving the content saved from a previous request made by the same client or even other clients.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Caching proxies keep local copies of frequently requested resources, allowing large organizations to significantly reduce their upstream bandwidth usage and costs, while significantly increasing performance.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Most ISPs and large businesses have a caching proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Caching proxies were the first kind of proxy server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Web proxies are commonly used to cache web pages from a web server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Poorly implemented caching proxies can cause problems, such as an inability to use user authentication.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy that is designed to mitigate specific link-related issues or degradation is a Performance Enhancing Proxy (PEPs).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] These are typically used to improve TCP performance in the presence of high round-trip times or high packet loss (such as wireless or mobile phone networks); or highly asymmetric links featuring very different upload and download rates.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] PEPs can make more efficient use of the network, for example, by merging TCP ACKs (acknowledgements) or compressing data sent at the application layer.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A translation proxy is a proxy server that is used to localize a website experience for different markets.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Traffic from the global audience is routed through the translation proxy to the source website.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] As visitors browse the proxied site, requests go back to the source site where pages are rendered.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The original language content in the response is replaced by the translated content as it passes back through the proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The translations used in a translation proxy can be either machine translation, human translation, or a combination of machine and human translation.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Different translation proxy implementations have different capabilities.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Some allow further customization of the source site for the local audiences, such as excluding the source content or substituting the source content with the original local content.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] An anonymous proxy server (sometimes called a web proxy) generally attempts to anonymize web surfing.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Anonymizers may be differentiated into several varieties.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The destination server (the server that ultimately satisfies the web request) receives requests from the anonymizing proxy server and thus does not receive information about the end user's address.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The requests are not anonymous to the anonymizing proxy server, however, and so a degree of trust is present between the proxy server and the user.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Many proxy servers are funded through a continuous advertising link to the user.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Advertisers use proxy servers for validating, checking, and quality assuring geotargeted ads.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A geotargeting ad server checks the request source IP address and uses a geo-IP database to determine the geographic source of requests.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Using a proxy server that is physically located inside a specific country or a city gives advertisers the ability to test geotargeted ads.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy can keep the internal network structure of a company secret by using network address translation, which can help the security of the internal network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This makes requests from machines and users on the local network anonymous.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies can also be combined with firewalls.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] An incorrectly configured proxy can provide access to a network otherwise isolated from the Internet.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies allow websites to make web requests to externally hosted resources (e.g., images, music files, etc.) when cross-domain restrictions prohibit the website from linking directly to the outside domains.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies also allow the browser to make web requests to externally hosted content on behalf of a website when cross-domain restrictions (in place to protect websites from the likes of data theft) prohibit the browser from directly accessing the outside domains.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Secondary market brokers use web proxy servers to circumvent restrictions on online purchases of limited products such as limited sneakers or tickets.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The request from the client is the same as a regular HTTP request except the full URL is passed, instead of just the path.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This request is sent to the proxy server, the proxy makes the request specified, and returns the response.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Some web proxies allow the HTTP CONNECT method to set up forwarding of arbitrary data through the connection; a common policy is to only forward port 443 to allow HTTPS traffic.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Examples of web proxy servers include Apache (with mod_proxy or Traffic Server), HAProxy, IIS configured as proxy (e.g., with Application Request Routing), Nginx, Privoxy, Squid, Varnish (reverse proxy only), WinGate, Ziproxy, Tinyproxy, RabbIT and Polipo.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] For clients, the problem of complex or multiple proxy-servers is solved by a client-server Proxy auto-config protocol (*PAC file*).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Various operating systems (such as Windows, Android, macOS, iOS, Xbox OS and PlayStation OS) and various browsers (such as Edge, Chrome, Safari and Firefox) can support Web proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] SOCKS also forwards arbitrary data after a connection phase, and is similar to HTTP CONNECT in web proxies.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] An **intercepting proxy** redirects or filters client traffic without being explicitly selected by the client.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] It is therefore often deployed without requiring browser or application proxy settings, and clients may be unaware that their traffic is passing through a proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In HTTP terminology, an interception proxy differs from a conventional HTTP proxy because it is not chosen by the user agent; instead, it is placed in the network path and filters or redirects outgoing traffic, commonly TCP port 80 traffic.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is a traffic filtering security feature that protects TCP servers from TCP SYN flood attacks, which are a type of denial-of-service attack.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is available for IP traffic only.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In 2009 a security flaw in the way that transparent proxies operate was published by Robert Auger, and the Computer Emergency Response Team issued an advisory listing dozens of affected transparent and intercepting proxy servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are commonly used in businesses to enforce acceptable use policies and to ease administrative overheads since no client browser configuration is required.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This second reason, however, is mitigated by features such as Active Directory group policy, or DHCP and automatic proxy detection.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are also commonly used by ISPs in some countries to save upstream bandwidth and improve customer response times by caching.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This is more common in countries where bandwidth is more limited (e.g, island nations) or must be paid for.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The diversion or interception of a TCP connection creates several issues.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] First, the original destination IP and port must somehow be communicated to the proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This is not always possible (e.g., where the gateway and proxy reside on different hosts).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] There is a class of cross-site attacks that depend on certain behaviors of intercepting proxies that do not check or have access to information about the original (intercepted) destination.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This problem may be resolved by using an integrated packet-level and application-level appliance or software, which is then able to communicate this information between the packet handler and the proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Intercepting also creates problems for HTTP authentication, especially connection-oriented authentication such as NTLM, as the client browser believes it is talking to a server rather than a proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This can cause problems where an intercepting proxy requires authentication, and then the user connects to a site that also requires authentication.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Finally, intercepting connections can cause problems for HTTP caches, as some requests and responses become uncacheable by a shared cache.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In integrated firewall/proxy servers where the router/firewall is on the same host as the proxy, communicating original destination information can be done by any method, for example, Microsoft TMG or WinGate.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Interception can also be performed using Cisco's WCCP (Web Cache Control Protocol).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This proprietary protocol resides on the router and is configured from the cache, allowing the cache to determine what ports and traffic are sent to it via transparent redirection from the router.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This redirection can occur in one of two ways: GRE tunneling (OSI Layer 3) or MAC rewrites (OSI Layer 2).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Once traffic reaches the proxy machine itself, interception is commonly performed with NAT (Network Address Translation).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Such setups are invisible to the client browser, but leave the proxy visible to the web server and other devices on the internet side of the proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Recent Linux and some BSD releases provide TPROXY (transparent proxy), which performs IP-level (OSI Layer 3) transparent interception and spoofing of outbound traffic, hiding the proxy IP address from other network devices.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A CGI web proxy accepts target URLs using a Web form in the user's browser window, processes the request, and returns the results to the user's browser.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Consequently, it can be used on a device or network that does not allow "true" proxy settings to be changed.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The first recorded CGI proxy, named "rover" at the time but renamed in 1998 to "CGIProxy", was developed by American computer scientist James Marshall in early 1996 for an article in "Unix Review" by Rich Morin.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The majority of CGI proxies are powered by one of CGIProxy (written in the Perl language), Glype (written in the PHP language), or PHProxy (written in the PHP language).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] As of April 2016, CGIProxy has received about two million downloads, Glype has received more than half a million downloads, whilst PHProxy still receives hundreds of downloads per week.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Despite waning in popularity due to VPNs and other privacy methods, as of September 2021 there are still a few hundred CGI proxies online.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Some CGI proxies were set up for purposes such as making websites more accessible to disabled people, but have since been shut down due to excessive traffic, usually caused by a third party advertising the service as a means to bypass local filtering.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Since many of these users do not care about the collateral damage they are causing, it became necessary for organizations to hide their proxies, disclosing the URLs only to those who take the trouble to contact the organization and demonstrate a genuine need.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A suffix proxy allows a user to access web content by appending the name of the proxy server to the URL of the requested content (e.g., "en.wikipedia.org.*SuffixProxy.com*").
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Suffix proxy servers are easier to use than regular proxy servers, but they do not offer high levels of anonymity, and their primary use is for bypassing web filters.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] However, this is rarely used due to more advanced web filters.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Tor is a system intended to provide online anonymity.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Tor client software routes Internet traffic through a worldwide volunteer network of servers for concealing a user's computer location or usage from someone conducting network surveillance or traffic analysis.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Using Tor makes tracing Internet activity more difficult, and is intended to protect users' personal freedom and their online privacy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] This reduces the possibility of the original data being unscrambled or understood in transit.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The I2P anonymous network ('I2P') is a proxy network aiming at online anonymity.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] It implements garlic routing, which is an enhancement of Tor's onion routing.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] I2P is fully distributed and works by encrypting all communications in various layers and relaying them through a network of routers run by volunteers in various locations.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] By keeping the source of the information hidden, I2P offers censorship resistance.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The goals of I2P are to protect users' personal freedom, privacy, and ability to conduct confidential business.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Each user of I2P runs an I2P router on their computer (node).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The I2P router takes care of finding other peers and building anonymizing tunnels through them.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] I2P provides proxies for all protocols (HTTP, IRC, SOCKS, ...).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The proxy concept refers to a layer-7 application in the OSI reference model.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Network address translation (NAT) is similar to a proxy but operates in layer 3.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] In the client configuration of layer-3 NAT, configuring the gateway is sufficient.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] However, for the client configuration of a layer-7 proxy, the destination of the packets that the client generates must always be the proxy server (layer 7), then the proxy server reads each packet and finds out the true destination.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Because NAT operates at layer 3, it is less resource-intensive than the layer-7 proxy, but also less flexible.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] As we compare these two technologies, we might encounter a terminology known as 'transparent firewall'.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] **Transparent firewall** means that the proxy uses the layer-7 proxy advantages without the knowledge of the client.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The client presumes that the gateway is a NAT in layer 3, and it does not have any idea about the inside of the packet, but through this method, the layer-3 packets are sent to the layer-7 proxy for investigation.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A DNS proxy server takes DNS queries from a (usually local) network and forwards them to an Internet Domain Name Server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Some client programs "SOCKS-ify" requests, which allows adaptation of any networked software to connect to external networks via certain types of proxy servers (mostly SOCKS).
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] A residential proxy (RESIP) is an intermediary that uses a real IP address provided by an Internet service provider with physical devices such as mobile phones and end-user computers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server, residential proxy users connect to the target through residential IP addresses.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] The target then identifies them as organic internet users.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] It does not let any tracking tool identify the reallocation of the user.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Any residential proxy can send any number of concurrent requests, and IP addresses are directly related to a specific region.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Unlike regular residential proxies, which hide the user's real IP address behind another IP address, rotating residential proxies, also known as *backconnect proxies*, conceal the user's real IP address behind a pool of proxies.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] These proxies switch between themselves at every session or at regular intervals.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Despite providers' assertions that the proxy hosts are voluntarily participating, numerous proxies are operated on potentially compromised hosts, including Internet of things devices.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] Through the process of cross-referencing the hosts, researchers have identified and analyzed logs that have been classified as potentially unwanted program and exposed a range of unauthorized activities conducted by RESIP hosts.
[src:sidecar-proxy/proxy-server] These activities encompassed illegal promotion, fast fluxing, phishing, hosting malware, and more.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:sidecar-proxy/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:sidecar-proxy/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:sidecar-proxy/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:sidecar-proxy/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:sidecar-proxy/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:sidecar-proxy/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:sidecar-proxy/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Sidecar containers are the secondary containers that run along with the main application container within the same Pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] These containers are used to enhance or to extend the functionality of the primary *app container* by providing additional services, or functionality such as logging, monitoring, security, or data synchronization, without directly altering the primary application code.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Typically, you only have one app container in a Pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] For example, if you have a web application that requires a local webserver, the local webserver is a sidecar and the web application itself is the app container.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Kubernetes implements sidecar containers as a special case of init containers; sidecar containers remain running after Pod startup.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] This document uses the term *regular init containers* to clearly refer to containers that only run during Pod startup.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Provided that your cluster has the `SidecarContainers` feature gate enabled (the feature is active by default since Kubernetes v1.29), you can specify a `restartPolicy` for containers listed in a Pod's `initContainers` field.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] These restartable *sidecar* containers are independent from other init containers and from the main application container(s) within the same pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] These can be started, stopped, or restarted without affecting the main application container and other init containers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] You can also run a Pod with multiple containers that are not marked as init or sidecar containers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] This is appropriate if the containers within the Pod are required for the Pod to work overall, but you don't need to control which containers start or stop first.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] You could also do this if you need to support older versions of Kubernetes that don't support a container-level `restartPolicy` field.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Kubernetes treats such containers as sidecars that continue running for the lifetime of the Pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] If an init container is created with its `restartPolicy` set to `Always`, it will start and remain running during the entire life of the Pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] This can be helpful for running supporting services separated from the main application containers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] If a `readinessProbe` is specified for this init container, its result will be used to determine the `ready` state of the Pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Since these containers are defined as init containers, they benefit from the same ordering and sequential guarantees as regular init containers, allowing you to mix sidecar containers with regular init containers for complex Pod initialization flows.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Compared to regular init containers, sidecars defined within `initContainers` continue to run after they have started.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] This is important when there is more than one entry inside `.spec.initContainers` for a Pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] After a sidecar-style init container is running (the kubelet has set the `started` status for that init container to true), the kubelet then starts the next init container from the ordered `.spec.initContainers` list.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] That status either becomes true because there is a process running in the container and no startup probe defined, or as a result of its `startupProbe` succeeding.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Upon Pod termination, the kubelet postpones terminating sidecar containers until the main application container has fully stopped.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] The sidecar containers are then shut down in the opposite order of their appearance in the Pod specification.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] This approach ensures that the sidecars remain operational, supporting other containers within the Pod, until their service is no longer required.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] If you define a Job that uses sidecar using Kubernetes-style init containers, the sidecar container in each Pod does not prevent the Job from completing after the main container has finished.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Sidecar containers run alongside *app containers* in the same pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] However, they do not execute the primary application logic; instead, they provide supporting functionality to the main application.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Sidecar containers have their own independent lifecycles.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] They can be started, stopped, and restarted independently of app containers.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] This means you can update, scale, or maintain sidecar containers without affecting the primary application.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Sidecar containers share the same network and storage namespaces with the primary container.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] This co-location allows them to interact closely and share resources.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] From a Kubernetes perspective, the sidecar container's graceful termination is less important.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] When other containers take all allotted graceful termination time, the sidecar containers will receive the `SIGTERM` signal, followed by the `SIGKILL` signal, before they have time to terminate gracefully.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] So exit codes different from `0` (`0` indicates successful exit), for sidecar containers are normal on Pod termination and should be generally ignored by the external tooling.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Sidecar containers work alongside the main container, extending its functionality and providing additional services.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Sidecar containers run concurrently with the main application container.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] They are active throughout the lifecycle of the pod and can be started and stopped independently of the main container.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Unlike init containers, sidecar containers support probes to control their lifecycle.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Sidecar containers can interact directly with the main application containers, because like init containers they always share the same network, and can optionally also share volumes (filesystems).
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Init containers stop before the main containers start up, so init containers cannot exchange messages with the app container in a Pod.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Any data passing is one-way (for example, an init container can put information inside an `emptyDir` volume).
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Changing the image of a sidecar container will not cause the Pod to restart, but will trigger a container restart.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] Quota and limits are applied based on the effective Pod request and limit.
[src:sidecar-proxy/sidecar-containers] On Linux, resource allocations for Pod level control groups (cgroups) are based on the effective Pod request and limit, the same as the scheduler.
